Anonymous Sun 21 Jun 2020 20:12:54 No.31051183 Report
Quoted By: >>31051502 >>31055025
Crab-eating foxes (or maikongs) form monogamic pairs to travel, hunt, and mate. They spend their time in their dens during the day (often stolen from a different animal, although they are capable of tunneling) and hunt during the night. They make use of several different sounds including barking, howling, and whirring sounds; often when a pair is separated. They are territorial, but are less so during the wet seasons where food is more abundant. Per it’s name, it searches for crabs on floodplains during the wet season, but it’s an opportunistic omnivore, and includes a vast amount of different animals in its diet. During the dry season, more insects are included in its diet. They seem to be rather docile, but that’s based on my own time watching videos of them. Breeding pair is monogamous and reproduction is not fixed to certain times of the year. They mate for life.
